

## 🧠 Concept

* A **peak element** is strictly greater than its neighbors
* Array may have multiple peaks → return **any one**
* Idea: move towards the **increasing side**, peak is guaranteed there

---

## ⚙️ Approach

* Pick `mid`
* Compare with right neighbor:

  * If `nums[mid] < nums[mid+1]` → move right
  * Else → move left
* Continue until peak is found

---

## 💻 Code


class Solution {
    public int findPeakElement(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;

        int si = 0;
        int ei = n - 1;

        while (si <= ei) {
            int mid = si + (ei - si) / 2;

            long right = (mid == n - 1) ? Long.MIN_VALUE : nums[mid + 1];
            long left  = (mid == 0) ? Long.MIN_VALUE : nums[mid - 1];

            if (nums[mid] > right && nums[mid] > left) {
                return mid;
            }

            if (nums[mid] < right) {
                si = mid + 1;
            } else {
                ei = mid - 1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```


## ⏱️ Complexity

* Time: `O(log n)`
* Space: `O(1)`

---

## 📌 Key Points

* Use `Long.MIN_VALUE` to safely handle boundaries
* If right side is bigger → peak lies on right
* Otherwise → peak lies on left
* No need to check all elements

